replies.comment info:
@Lilly 

Greetings from up the road in Jersey! While it seems like it has been raining here forever, the declining groundwater supply is very much in the forefront in other parts of the country. You make some interesting comments on some of the products of in the first graph, why do you suppose some of the more water efficient products don't also show up in that first graph?  Is it a matter of people just not eating their vegetables? Is chicken enough, or do we need to move on to a more vegetarian diet?

You just made me think about all of the new products like 'The impossible Burger.'  I wonder what sort of water costs are involved with these new 'meats."

@Emily P3 

Hi Emily.  it completely makes sense that you've honed in on chicken and cheese (by the way why do you think that the graph highlights chicken and cheese? beef and pork are consumed in greater quantities and in your generation, beef, pork, and cheese all seem to be growing at the same rate). 

I wonder if you think Chicken is a good choice.  Its 1/4 the water cost of beef but it is still twice the cost of things lentils and beans. Does that matter?

@Lucy 

Hello Lucy. First of all I really like your headline! I have many of the same wonderings.  What is it that causes the fluctuations in the popularity of some of these foods?  Presenting these graphs together, one might think that there are environmental factors but is one really caused by the other? 

Come back Friday and you'll get links to the full article that these graphs come from and, hopefully, some more things to wonder about.

@Connor Mounts 

Hello Connor.  You are spot on about the chicken and cheese consumption.  Do you think that accounts for some of the issues we have had regarding low groundwater levels in parts of the United States? 

Your headline makes we wonder.  Do you attribute the low levels of ground water to 'producing' different foods? Or producing 'produce' itself?

@Brooke Z 

I noticed many of the same things you did.  I wonder if you think the increase in chicken consumption is related to the fact the water cost of producing chicken is 1/4 the cost of producing beef? Or are there other factors involved in the increase in chicken consumption that are not addressed in the graphs?

Be sure to come back Friday for the reveal and see how some of these trends fit into our greater global context.

@Jessica AOSE 

* missed second graph 

The second graph compares Americans' diets and favorite foods to the amount of water required to produce one pound of these items. Pork requires the most water to produce when compared to chicken and cheese. I'm curious if this is why cheese and chicken are more popular because they are easier to make and require less water.
